<subSubSection id="209E1AAD0D6DB26DFF66F936FE531531" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="1" pageNumber="40" type="description">
<paragraph id="683B49260D6DB26FFF66F936FE4611FE" blockId="1.[151,683,1647,1710]" box="[151,439,1683,1710]" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">
(
<figureCitation id="F0BF55A30D6DB26FFF6EF936FEC511FD" box="[159,308,1683,1709]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1702,1726]" captionTargetBox="[277,1310,234,1676]" captionTargetId="figure-39@2.[277,1310,234,1676]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Crossomeles copei sp. nov., holotype male. a) Dorsal habitus. b) Close-up of pronotum. c) Close-up of head. d) Lateral habitus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577706/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">Figures 1a–d</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="F0BF55A30D6DB26FFEB1F936FE5E11FE" box="[320,431,1683,1710]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1744,1768]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,181,1720]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[158,1429,181,1720]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Four species of Crossomeles. a) C. acutipennis, paratype male, close-up of head. b) C. aureopilis, paratype male, close-up of head. c) C. copei, holotype male, close-up of head. d) C. oscarcastilloi sp. nov., holotype male, close-up of head. e) C. acutipennis, paratype male, close-up of pronotum. f) C. aureopilis, paratype male, close-up of pronotum. g) C. copei, holotype male, close-up of pronotum. h) C. oscarcastilloi sp. nov., holotype male, close-up of pronotum. i) C. acutipennis, paratype male, close-up of metatibia. j) C. aureopilis, paratype male, close-up of metatibia. k) C. copei, holotype male, close-up of metatibia. l) C. oscarcastilloi sp. nov., holotype male, close-up of metatibia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577714/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">
5c, 
<quantity id="AF7CE4C30D6DB26FFE99F936FE7611FE" box="[360,391,1683,1710]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="5.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="40" unit="g" value="5.0">5g</quantity>
, 5k
</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="683B49260D6DB26FFF66F97EFD19106E" blockId="1.[151,1436,1755,2034]" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6DB26FFF66F97EFED011A5" bold="true" box="[151,289,1755,1781]" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">Description</emphasis>
. Male (
<figureCitation id="F0BF55A30D6DB26FFE8AF97EFE0411A5" box="[379,501,1755,1781]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1702,1726]" captionTargetBox="[277,1310,234,1676]" captionTargetId="figure-39@2.[277,1310,234,1676]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Crossomeles copei sp. nov., holotype male. a) Dorsal habitus. b) Close-up of pronotum. c) Close-up of head. d) Lateral habitus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577706/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">Figs. 1a–d</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="F0BF55A30D6DB26FFDF3F97EFDAB11A6" box="[514,602,1755,1782]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1744,1768]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,181,1720]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[158,1429,181,1720]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Four species of Crossomeles. a) C. acutipennis, paratype male, close-up of head. b) C. aureopilis, paratype male, close-up of head. c) C. copei, holotype male, close-up of head. d) C. oscarcastilloi sp. nov., holotype male, close-up of head. e) C. acutipennis, paratype male, close-up of pronotum. f) C. aureopilis, paratype male, close-up of pronotum. g) C. copei, holotype male, close-up of pronotum. h) C. oscarcastilloi sp. nov., holotype male, close-up of pronotum. i) C. acutipennis, paratype male, close-up of metatibia. j) C. aureopilis, paratype male, close-up of metatibia. k) C. copei, holotype male, close-up of metatibia. l) C. oscarcastilloi sp. nov., holotype male, close-up of metatibia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577714/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">5c, g, k</figureCitation>
). Length 
<quantity id="AF7CE4C30D6DB26FFD39F97EFC9D11A6" box="[712,876,1755,1782]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" metricValueMax="1.75" metricValueMin="1.65" pageId="1" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="17.0" valueMax="17.5" valueMin="16.5">16.5–17.5 mm</quantity>
(measured from frons to abdominal apex), width 
<quantity id="AF7CE4C30D6DB26FFF66F95AFEEC104A" box="[151,285,1791,1818]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="2.2" pageId="1" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="2.25" valueMax="2.3" valueMin="2.2">2.2–2.3 mm</quantity>
(measured across humeri). Habitus as in 
<figureCitation id="F0BF55A30D6DB26FFD17F95AFCC71049" box="[742,822,1791,1817]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1702,1726]" captionTargetBox="[277,1310,234,1676]" captionTargetId="figure-39@2.[277,1310,234,1676]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Crossomeles copei sp. nov., holotype male. a) Dorsal habitus. b) Close-up of pronotum. c) Close-up of head. d) Lateral habitus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577706/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">Fig. 1a</figureCitation>
. Form moderate sized, elongate; integument testaceous with portions black, dark brown, and reddish orange.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="683B49260D6DB26CFF36F8E2FE3F1785" blockId="1.[151,1436,1755,2034]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,150,213]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="41" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6DB26FFF36F8E2FEFD1031" bold="true" box="[199,268,1863,1890]" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6DB26FFF36F8E2FEF41032" bold="true" box="[199,261,1863,1890]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">Head</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Frons black with fine, dense yellow pubescence; eyes large, globose, narrowly separated in front by about 6 ommatidia; frons with narrow, shallow median suture; genae about 1/4 as long as lower eye lobe (
<figureCitation id="F0BF55A30D6DB26FFACAF8CEFA6710D5" box="[1339,1430,1899,1925]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1702,1726]" captionTargetBox="[277,1310,234,1676]" captionTargetId="figure-39@2.[277,1310,234,1676]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Crossomeles copei sp. nov., holotype male. a) Dorsal habitus. b) Close-up of pronotum. c) Close-up of head. d) Lateral habitus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577706/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">Figs. 1c</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="F0BF55A30D6DB26FFF66F82AFF4510FA" box="[151,180,1935,1962]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1744,1768]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,181,1720]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[158,1429,181,1720]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Four species of Crossomeles. a) C. acutipennis, paratype male, close-up of head. b) C. aureopilis, paratype male, close-up of head. c) C. copei, holotype male, close-up of head. d) C. oscarcastilloi sp. nov., holotype male, close-up of head. e) C. acutipennis, paratype male, close-up of pronotum. f) C. aureopilis, paratype male, close-up of pronotum. g) C. copei, holotype male, close-up of pronotum. h) C. oscarcastilloi sp. nov., holotype male, close-up of pronotum. i) C. acutipennis, paratype male, close-up of metatibia. j) C. aureopilis, paratype male, close-up of metatibia. k) C. copei, holotype male, close-up of metatibia. l) C. oscarcastilloi sp. nov., holotype male, close-up of metatibia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577714/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">5c</figureCitation>
); vertex irregularly punctate; antennae extending to near apex of abdominal segment II; antennomeres orangish to brownish; antennomeres I–VI with several long and erect setae beneath, VI–XI slightly expanded apically; with small, indistinct sensory pores on dorsal and ventral surface of each antennomere. Antennal formula based on length of antennomere III: scape=0.70; II=0.25; III=1.00; IV=0.55; V=0.90; VI=0.80; VII=0.85; VIII=0.80; IX=0.75; X=0.70; XI=0.80.
</paragraph>
<caption id="3CFB19AE0D6EB26CFF66F903FEC711B2" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577706" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6577706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577706/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="41" startId="2.[151,250,1702,1726]" targetBox="[277,1310,234,1676]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph id="683B49260D6EB26CFF66F903FEC711B2" blockId="2.[151,1437,1702,1762]" pageId="2" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6EB26CFF66F903FEE511EE" bold="true" box="[151,276,1702,1726]" pageId="2" pageNumber="41">FIGURE 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="AF8432A50D6EB26CFEEDF903FE2A11EE" authority="Nearns &amp; Swift, 2022" authorityName="Nearns &amp; Swift" authorityYear="2022" box="[284,475,1702,1726]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Crossomeles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="copei" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6EB26CFEEDF903FE2A11EE" box="[284,475,1702,1726]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="41">Crossomeles copei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6EB26CFE13F903FDC511EE" bold="true" box="[482,564,1702,1726]" pageId="2" pageNumber="41">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="41C3284F0D6EB26CFE13F903FDC511EE" box="[482,564,1702,1726]" pageId="2" pageNumber="41" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, holotype male. 
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6EB26CFD10F903FD0611EE" bold="true" box="[737,759,1702,1726]" pageId="2" pageNumber="41">a)</emphasis>
Dorsal habitus. 
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6EB26CFC51F903FC4711EE" bold="true" box="[928,950,1702,1726]" pageId="2" pageNumber="41">b)</emphasis>
Close-up of pronotum. 
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6EB26CFB5CF903FB3011EE" bold="true" box="[1197,1217,1702,1726]" pageId="2" pageNumber="41">c)</emphasis>
Close-up of head. 
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6EB26CFA77F903FA6C11EE" bold="true" box="[1414,1437,1702,1726]" pageId="2" pageNumber="41">d)</emphasis>
Lateral habitus.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="683B49260D6EB26DFF36F8B5FC771611" blockId="2.[151,1437,1808,2015]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,861]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="2" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6EB26CFF36F8B5FED5107A" bold="true" box="[199,292,1808,1835]" pageId="2" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6EB26CFF36F8B5FEEC107B" bold="true" box="[199,285,1808,1835]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="41">Thorax</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Pronotum black, elongate, subcylindrical, about 1.20 times as long as wide (
<figureCitation id="F0BF55A30D6EB26CFB59F8B5FAD6107A" box="[1192,1319,1808,1834]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1702,1726]" captionTargetBox="[277,1310,234,1676]" captionTargetId="figure-39@2.[277,1310,234,1676]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Crossomeles copei sp. nov., holotype male. a) Dorsal habitus. b) Close-up of pronotum. c) Close-up of head. d) Lateral habitus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577706/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="41">Figs. 1a, b</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="F0BF55A30D6EB26CFAC7F8B5FAA4107B" box="[1334,1365,1808,1835]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1744,1768]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,181,1720]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[158,1429,181,1720]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Four species of Crossomeles. a) C. acutipennis, paratype male, close-up of head. b) C. aureopilis, paratype male, close-up of head. c) C. copei, holotype male, close-up of head. d) C. oscarcastilloi sp. nov., holotype male, close-up of head. e) C. acutipennis, paratype male, close-up of pronotum. f) C. aureopilis, paratype male, close-up of pronotum. g) C. copei, holotype male, close-up of pronotum. h) C. oscarcastilloi sp. nov., holotype male, close-up of pronotum. i) C. acutipennis, paratype male, close-up of metatibia. j) C. aureopilis, paratype male, close-up of metatibia. k) C. copei, holotype male, close-up of metatibia. l) C. oscarcastilloi sp. nov., holotype male, close-up of metatibia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577714/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="41">
<quantity id="AF7CE4C30D6EB26CFAC7F8B5FAA4107B" box="[1334,1365,1808,1835]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="5.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="41" unit="g" value="5.0">5g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
); disk coarsely, deeply, subconfluently alveolate, pubescence dense across apex, base, and down sides dense; prosternum clothed with long, suberect setae; mesoventrite densely clothed at sides with fine, golden, appressed pubescence; metaventrite moderately densely punctate, moderately densely clothed with short, golden, appressed pubescence along top margin and on posterior end. Mesanepisternum densely clothed with appressed pale yellow pubescence. Mesepimeron with sparse pale yellow setae. Metanespisternum with sparse pale yellow setae on anterior half, densely clothed with appressed pale yellow pubescence on posterior half. Scutellum densely clothed with appressed pale yellow pubescence. Elytra extending to near base of abdominal segment I; disk shining, testaceous, base yellowish inside of humeri, humeri orangish, margins narrowly black; punctures moderately dense, becoming finer toward apex; pubescence sparse, long, erect and suberect, each seta rising out of a puncture; each elytron strongly dehiscent and narrowing from behind basal fourth; apices rounded.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="683B49260D6FB26DFF36FEEEFCF71681" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,861]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6FB26DFF36FEEEFEF41635" bold="true" box="[199,261,331,357]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6FB26DFF36FEEEFF0C1635" bold="true" box="[199,253,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Legs</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Pro- and mesolegs reddish orange; pro- and mesofemora strongly clavate, short; metafemora elongate, widening slightly at apical third; basal half brownish, apical half reddish orange (
<figureCitation id="F0BF55A30D6FB26DFBCFFECAFB6016DA" box="[1086,1169,367,394]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1702,1726]" captionTargetBox="[277,1310,234,1676]" captionTargetId="figure-39@2.[277,1310,234,1676]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Crossomeles copei sp. nov., holotype male. a) Dorsal habitus. b) Close-up of pronotum. c) Close-up of head. d) Lateral habitus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577706/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Fig. 1d</figureCitation>
); metatibiae with basal half brownish black, apical half reddish orange; with a sparse brush of orangish setae on apical two-thirds (
<figureCitation id="F0BF55A30D6FB26DFACDFE36FA7E16FD" box="[1340,1423,402,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1744,1768]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,181,1720]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[158,1429,181,1720]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Four species of Crossomeles. a) C. acutipennis, paratype male, close-up of head. b) C. aureopilis, paratype male, close-up of head. c) C. copei, holotype male, close-up of head. d) C. oscarcastilloi sp. nov., holotype male, close-up of head. e) C. acutipennis, paratype male, close-up of pronotum. f) C. aureopilis, paratype male, close-up of pronotum. g) C. copei, holotype male, close-up of pronotum. h) C. oscarcastilloi sp. nov., holotype male, close-up of pronotum. i) C. acutipennis, paratype male, close-up of metatibia. j) C. aureopilis, paratype male, close-up of metatibia. k) C. copei, holotype male, close-up of metatibia. l) C. oscarcastilloi sp. nov., holotype male, close-up of metatibia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577714/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Fig. 5k</figureCitation>
). Metatarsomere I distinctly longer than II–IV combined.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="683B49260D6FB26DFF36FE7FFE4F156D" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,861]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6FB26DFF36FE7FFECD16A5" bold="true" box="[199,316,474,501]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Elongate, slender, broadening slightly toward apex, predominantly yellow with portions reddishorange (
<figureCitation id="F0BF55A30D6FB26DFF03FE5AFE9A154A" box="[242,363,511,538]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1702,1726]" captionTargetBox="[277,1310,234,1676]" captionTargetId="figure-39@2.[277,1310,234,1676]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Crossomeles copei sp. nov., holotype male. a) Dorsal habitus. b) Close-up of pronotum. c) Close-up of head. d) Lateral habitus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577706/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Figs. 1a, d</figureCitation>
); ventrites progressively more densely punctate from first; pubescence sparse; last ventrite shallowly impressed medially.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="683B49260D6FB26DFF36FDE3FE531531" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,861]" box="[199,418,582,609]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6FB26DFF36FDE3FED41531" bold="true" box="[199,293,582,609]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6FB26DFF36FDE3FEEF1531" bold="true" box="[199,286,582,609]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Female</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="209E1AAD0D6FB26DFF36FDCFFDCD159D" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="683B49260D6FB26DFF36FDCFFDCD159D" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,861]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis id="5AF095340D6FB26DFF36FDCFFE2915D5" bold="true" box="[199,472,618,645]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Diagnosis and remarks</emphasis>
. This species can be separated from congeners by the elytra shorter, extending to about base of abdominal segment I, broadly rounded apically; metatibiae without dense brush of suberect setae; and genae about a 1/4 as long as lower eye lobe.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
